    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-04-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-04-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="103"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d103">
                <head>103. Memorandum for the Record of a Meeting, Department of State, Washington,
                    April 1, 1960<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d103fn1">Source: Department of
                        State, Central Files, 371.707/4–160. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_DJC1"
                            >Dreier</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1960-04-01">April 1, 1960</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Draft Statute of the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PRESENT</head>
                    <item>The Secretary</item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_ARA1">ARA</gloss> — Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RRRJ1"
                            >Rubottom</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_L1">L</gloss> — Mr. <persName>Hager</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_H1">H</gloss> — Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MWBJ1"
                            >Macomber</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_IO1">IO</gloss> — Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HHE1"
                            >Henderson</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_ARA1">ARA</gloss> — Amb. <persName corresp="#p_DJC1"
                            >Dreier</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <pb facs="0390" n="350" xml:id="pg_350"/>
                <p>After a lengthy discussion of the whole matter, the Secretary expressed the view
                    that we should not approve the statute of the Inter-American Commission on Human
                    Rights. He did not favor our securing the adoption of an article that would
                    limit the application of Articles 11–f, 20, 22 and 23 to those states which
                    specifically accepted, as proposed by <gloss target="#t_ARA1">ARA</gloss>.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d103fn2">A memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_RRRJ1"
                            >Rubottom</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName>,
                        March 29, reads as follows: “<gloss target="#t_ARA1">ARA</gloss> believes
                        that the best solution to this problem is for the United States to take the
                        position that we will approve the statute if an article is included saying,
                        in effect, that those articles of the statute under which specific cases of
                        alleged violations would be considered shall be applicable only to those
                        countries whose governments specifically accept them.” (<hi rend="italic"
                            >Ibid</hi>., 371.707/2–1060)</note>
                </p>
                <p>He urged that we make clear we favored a commission which would exercise the
                    general functions of promoting respect for human rights, such as set forth in
                    Articles 11–a to e, but that we should draw the line at that point.</p>
            </div>
